  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes, good approach -- one concern about 现象仁 vs 仁",
    "content": "Yes, this is the right approach. It follows standard practice for philosophical translations from Chinese (Graham and Ziporyn both do this). Two brief points:\n\n**The format is sound.** Preserving the 文言 original is essential -- these are canonical texts that the reader may want to compare against other translations. The inline gloss on first occurrence gives the reader the key, and dropping it afterward keeps the prose clean. No concerns about clutter if the glosses are limited to first occurrence per essay.\n\n**One concern: the author's 现象X terms.** The 道德仁义礼 analysis in 后形而上学 creates a systematic distinction between the traditional term (仁) and the author's phenomenological reinterpretation (现象仁, \"phenomenal humaneness\"). These are *not the same concept* -- the whole argument turns on the difference between 仁-as-observed-in-phenomena and 仁-as-metaphysical-principle. The translation format needs to make this distinction visually clear.\n\nRecommendation: when the author uses 现象仁, render it as \"phenomenal humaneness\" (italicized or marked) to distinguish it from bare \"humaneness\" when the author refers to the traditional metaphysical concept. The reader must be able to track which layer the author is operating on at any given moment -- this is the load-bearing distinction of that entire passage. A brief TN on first occurrence of 现象仁 explaining the author's coinage (\"phenomenal humaneness: the author's term for humaneness as actually experienced in phenomena, as distinct from humaneness as a metaphysical principle\") would suffice."
  }
}
